commit_message: Initial setup with a versioning class.
BackupCLI can now request the current backup version.
Removed the configuration source, renamed the constant to LIB_PATH.
Created a basic sample configuration which the configuration parser will be based off of.
Cleaned up whitespace.
Renamed the sample configuration.
Global configuration for S3 can now be set.
Added the model class. Added the ability to add adapters to the Model.
Added the ability to set the Mail default configuration.
Renamed the S3 spec file and corrected a comment.
Completely removed the fixtures for now.
Added the base of storage adding.
Fixed adapters.
Added base adapter setup for MySQL.
Removed the fixtures path constant for now.
Finished implementing the initial setup for the MySQL adapter. Added a CLI module and using FileUtils library.
Backup now includes the YAML library.
Added a TMP_PATH constant and incorporated it in to the MySQL adapter.
Cleaned up the perform method.
Finished implementing the basic Storage structure and the initial storage method: Amazon S3 (Backup::Storage::S3)
Added a flag for marking a file as 'transferred' and added the ability to remove transferred files from the amazon s3. storage objects now also log the time they are initialized.
Renamed Adapters to Databases. Also renamed the database Database attribute to name.
Removed some spec boilerplate.
Fixed some inconsistencies in the source.
Added a demonstration perform! method to the Model class that will perform the backup.
Added the Backup::Finder, which looks through all the instantiated models and returns the requested one.
Improved comments.
Improved the backup binary for the 'perform' command.
Refactored the unix_utility in to the Backup::CLI module to make it re-usable in other classes other than just the Backup::Database::MySQL class.
Fixed an issue where the wrong file would be uploaded to Amazon S3.

Backup::Model now includes the Backup::CLI module to make use of the cli utility method. Added the private method package! to package all the dumped and archived data in to a single .tar file which then is ready for potential compression, encryption before the transfer.

S3 will no longer automatically create the bucket. The user has to do this manually since it's very brittle. Unsure whether it's Fog or Amazon S3 itself. Some regions work, some don't and raise heavy response errors.
When an incorrect region is specified, Backup now provides more user friendly feedback.
Backup now cleans up after itself, removing all generated temporary files.
Models can now create archives.
Added the Archive class which allows users to archive files and folders in to the backup file.

Fixed the issue where if all tests were run at the same time, the Backup::Archive specs would fail because the class was re-opened in the model spec. All class definitions have been placed in a before/do block to ensure they are isolated from other specs.
Used &> /dev/null to silence the tar -c message: 'Removing leading '/' from member names'.
Added a message at the start of a backup initialization to inform the user the backup for the particular trigger has started.
Added the archives description.
Added the GZip compressor. Now the file extension will dynamically change as a class variable. Every time a compression occurs it'll append another extension to the stack.
Removed old commented out line.

Cleaned up the class methods/variables in the Backup::Model. Added more comments and methods that returns the current file (full path and current extension), and the temporary path of the corresponding model.
Added the OpenSSL Encryptor.
All constants are now nicely namespaced within the Backup module. No more global littering!
Fixed the problem where the current file wouldn't be transferred.
Added the rm method to the Backup::CLI module.
The Backup::Encryptor::OpenSSL will now remove the non-encrypted file after encrypting the file (which produces a new encrypted file).
Changed the '-a' option to '-base64'. It does the same but is more expressing.

Improved Backup::Compressor::Gzip a lot. Added more comments. Instead of using an additional_options array, you can now provide either a c.best or c.fast option to make the compression either better or faster. Some code has also been tidied up within this class.
Passing a block with configuration options to the Backup::Storage::S3 class is now optional since you can set everything in the Backup::Configuration::S3.
Cleaned up some code in the Backup::Storage::Base and Backup::Storage::S3 files.
Fixed some whitespace and changed the comment decoration in the version file.
Added the placeholder README file.
Updated the runtime dependencies. Added Thor.
Removed some whitespace from the backup binary.
Noted that Backup 3 is tested against Ruby 1.8.7 and Ruby 1.9.2
Updated Gemlock file with latest Fog and Thor versions to date.
Added a links to the Backup 2 branch, wiki, issues, gems.
Made a bunch of methods private, removed old connected attribute since it's no longer used.
Added environment paths. Added more options to the perform command of the CLI to manipulate these default paths.
Forgot to indent a few commits ago.
Ensure that a folder gets created with the TRIGGER name inside the DATA_PATH.
Added the ability to provide a @keep attribute for every storage method to tell Backup how many backups you want to keep at each storage location. This feature is called Cycling and is now available.
Added the ability to use constants inside the configuration file when defining databases, storages, encryptors and compressors.

The Backup::Model.extension class variable should not be set every time a model gets instantiated. It'll be defined only once when the class is first loaded in memory, and then only further appended after certain backup procedures.

Improving the DSL by allowing to use constants to define the databases, encryptors, compressors failed in Ruby 1.8.7. This issue has been addressed and the new class definitions have been moved to a more suitable location (Backup model, instead of Backup::Model class) and they define classes in Backup::Finder instead of Backup::Model, a more suitable and isolated location.
Removed boiler plate in the Backup::Model#perform! method by using single-line blocks rather than multi-line.
Refactored a lot of code for the global configuration and storage features.
Added the base of the notifier. Refactored A LOT and abstracted A LOT to DRY things up.
Underscores are also part of method names and should be matchable.
Added comments to the S3 global configuration class.
Applied a better file structure for the configuration. Moved everything configuration related in to folders and sub-folders within lib/configuration.
Added Notifiers (Mail) to allow users to be notified by email when a backup succeeds or fails.
Improved readability of the notifiers/mail.rb class. Improved mail specs.

Fixed a Ruby 1.8.7 => 1.9.2 bug. Can't append a RuntimeError object to a String, in Ruby 1.8.7 it'd automatically call .to_s on the exception object, but not in Ruby 1.9.2, now I force it to convert to a string before the concatenation.

Emails no longer get generated by raw strings. Instead we're now using Ruby's ERB library to read template files (which are created in this commit) and bind objects to them. This cleans up the code base a lot, making it more readable and re-usable. Also, the emails are now a bit more detailed and visually better.
Updated all gems and added the Timecop gem to help testing with Time objects.

Updated the two system files .rspec and .infinity_test. The rspec test console will now output with colorized text. InfinityTest will now run the whole suite every time a file gets saved inside the backup/lib directory.
Added the Backup:Logger.
Added comments to the Backup executable file. Improved some textual CLI output.
Whitespace.
Fixed incorrect comment.
Abstracted Backup::Database by adding a base class with two destructive methods. This enabled logging for Backup::Database:MySQL.
Added logging messages to Backup::Archive.

Added logging to the Backup::Compressor::Base (abstract) and implemented it in Backup::Compressor::Gzip.
Forgot to stub out particular methods for the Backup::Compressor::Gzip specs.

Added Backup::Logger to Notifier.

Added comments for each of the log! methods.
Erb library should only be loaded if it'll actually be used to reduce memory consumption.
Initial setup for PostgreSQL.
Fixed a bug where the folder would not be archived properly as a .tar. This update also makes the packaged .tar nicely organized when unpacked to a folder containing sub-folders and files.

Added the ability to override Backup's auto-detection for utilities such as mongodump by providing the full path (using the 'utility_path') method (applies to all databases, since this is base functionality).
Made DSL more consistent by changing PostgreSQL and MySQL's database 'user' to 'username'. Cleaned up some internal syntax and improved/added more specs.

Added support for SFTP protocols.
Backup now supports SCP protocols for transferring backups to remote servers.
FTP protocol now also removes the preceding ~/ from the @path if it exists.

When the FTP protocol tries to remove a file from the remote location, and it fails due to the file not existing, it will no longer raise an exception, but instead issue a warning and proceed as normal.
Added defaults to the FTP, SFTP and SCP protocols. (@port and @path)
Backup 3 now allows users to specify a specific path inside a S3, CloudFiles or Dropbox storage by providing a @path.
Cleaned up whitespace.
When a backup process is initialized, it'll try to find the model, if it does, it'll now add the reference to that model object to the Backup::Model.current class attribute.
Removed some lines for the begin rescue end blocks.
When @keep is 0, it should not throw away every backup, instead, 0 will mean: unlimited, similar to nil.

Added a silent logger.

Implemented the initial foundation code base for Syncers. Syncers are similar to Storages, except that these bypass the whole copying/organizing, packaging, compressing, encrypting procedures entirely and directly sync folders from your server's filesystem to a backup server. This approach is a lot less CPU intensive for backing up large (gigabytes) of images, music, videos and other heavy file types.

Removed hard dependencies. With this, Backup will no longer install every single dependency when installing the Backup gem. A new class (Backup::Dependency) has been implemented to handle the dependency management and versioning so users can cherry-pick what gems they need to perform their backups. Backup will provide the command to install the necessary gem and appropriate version if the requirements aren't met.
Added Amazon Simple Storage Service (S3) to the list of available Syncers.

Improved the Backup::Dependency manager. It'll now display detailed information on what to do when a dependency is required, but not installed. It'll now also try to install the dependency for you so you don't have to.

Exception will now be rescued when Backup tries to remove a non-existent file from Dropbox and proceed with the process as expected by removing the entry from the stored data directory.

Added Backup::Exception::CommandNotFound when command line utilities cannot be found and the OS returns a 32512 error.Added a method for Backup::CLI ( #raise_if_command_not_found! ) that handles throwing exceptions when Backup::CLI runs a command of which the main utility could not be found (e.g. mysqldump, mongodump).nnThe Logger now has a Logger.normal method that simply does a regular puts command, but at the same time, logs to the backup.log for debugging purposes. This is now used when exceptions are thrown since it would previously not log exceptions to the backup.log which made it harder to debug issues.nnBackup now handles any time of exception that may be raised and gives a more detailed output as well. Rather than using ENV variables, Backup now uses Ruby's built-in constants since the ENV variables sometimes appeared to not display particular details. Now the RUBY_PLATFORM is also included for better debugging. Also the exception's class name will be displayed from now on.nnFinally, The email notifier template has been updated with all these details, so now detailed information will be displayed in the console, in the backup.log and in the email notifications to make debugging and tracking the issues easier.

Releasing version 3.0.14 which fixes the tar utility for FreeBSD (and possibly other OS'). This release also drastically improves the way exceptions are handled. It'll now properly log full exceptions to the backup.log, Backup now uses Ruby's built-in constants rather than the ENV constants to get information about the process environment (more dependable source) and exceptions will now get raised when a utility cannot be found when Backup tries to use it (mysqldump, pgdump, tar, gzip, openssl, etc), and will kill the process rather than continuing and ignoring the issue.

Instead of automatically installing dependencies, simply provide instructions for the user to follow to ensure gem dependencies are installed in the proper locations. (RVM, RBenv, System, etc).

Updated a few dependency versions (particularly API gems) and relax the dependency constraints with `>=` instead of `~>` since API's tend to change quite frequently, gems might update faster as well. API gems that update fast tend to break backwards compatibility or break the API and usually need to be up-to-date, using >= makes Backup users independent of Backup API gem dependency versions and does not require Backup to urgently update the dependency list every time. Fixed Dropbox to work with Backup::Splitter. Backup::Storage::Dropbox now instance variable caches the connection so that it doesn't hammer the Dropbox service. The instance variable gets removed when finished processing all chunks. Instead of deleting one file at a time from Dropbox, now it simply deletes the whole folder in a single API call. The name of the file that's being uploaded differs from what the remote file name should be named, now using :as => remote_file to change the filename on the Dropbox server to the final result.

Fixed adding support for Backup::Splitter to Backup::Storage::Ninefold. Should not request the directory for each chunk. Added a logger to log every chunk that gets deleted. Delete each chunk and once all chunks have been deleted, remove the empty directory to clean up the filesystem.

Finished fixing issues with Backup::Splitter combined with Storage::[FTP|SFTP|SCP|RSync|Local] and made them all compatible. Storage::RSync is still independent of backup cycling and will also be independent of backup splitting and will not use these methods.

Updated all the Database classes, and the Archive class. Moved the #prepare! and #log! methods from #initialize and #perform! in to the Backup::Database::Base class in the #perform! super-method. Now, instead of running #prepare! and #log! from within the child (Database) class, we invoke it from the Backup::Database::Base class by calling #super in the child (Database) class's #perform! method. This cleans up / refactors / abstracts code, and also fixes the WILDCARD triggering issue.
Get rid of all debug options for Backup::Syncer::RSync. Particularly the -P option caused file transfer issues.

Ensure absolute (full path) using File.expand_path(path) rather than using relative paths and  ~  for $HOME. This provides more flexibility in the backup configuration file, improves the readability of the code and makes the overall implementation more solid and the generated paths more consistent.

Removed `2> /dev/null` for the `tar` utility since we're using the POpen4 library now. STDOUT is already being silenced from the Backup::Logger thanks to POpen4. `2> /dev/null` caused the STDERR to be silenced when an exception occurred, so users had a hard time figuring out what the problem was. This has now been fixed.

Revamped the Backup::CLI module. Removed the CommandNotFound exception and method since the CommandFailed exception already picks it up, and it isn't necessary to check whether the command isn't found twice. Also, it is now possible to pass in an array of exit codes to ignore in to the #run method, rather than raising an exception when a non-0 exit code gets returned. Cleaned up the rest of the code in the cli.rb file.

The Backup::Archive now ignores the exit(1) code, as it only indicates that the files in one or more of the directories that are being archived have changed since the archive was being read by the `tar` utility. This can happen when a folder that's constantly updated by for example user data from a website (e.g. user uploads) and you do not want backup to abort every single time someone uploads a new file during the archiving process. The new file will be picked up during the next backup process and ignored during the current one rather than aborting the whole backup operation.

Update Logger to better support Syslog addition- Adds command line options --syslog/--no-syslog,n  as well as --logfile/--no-logfile to disable loggingn  to Backup's native log file.n- Logger may also be configured using Logger.configure {...}n  within the user's config.rb file. This was primarily to allow settingn  other Syslog options. To support this, the `backup perform` startupn  process was modified and the Logger now buffers all messages itn  receives until configuration can be completed.nnOther side-effects:nn- `backup perform` will now exit with an error if no Models can be foundn  for the triggers given. Previously this would not occur if the triggern  used a wildcard.n- If two Models have the same trigger, they will now both be performed.n  Previously only the first found Model would be performed.n

patch dropbox-ruby-sdk-1.5.1- Ensure @file_obj's pos matches @offsetn- Handle a DropboxError that has no #http_response,n  is not an HTTPResponse or has a malformed body.nnThe server will return error 400 if the offset sent does not matchnthe offset expected, and returns the expected offset. v.1.5.1 willnset @offset to the expected offset (if less than what's expected),nthen read a new chunk from @file_obj, but does not ensure @file_obj'snpos is correct. If @offset is greater than the expected, it willnendlessly retry the same failed request.nFor any other error, if the error is rescued and #upload is callednagain to retry the chunk (as is done in the SDK's example code),nthe client does not ensure that @file_obj's pos is correct.nIt also assumes successful responses will include an offset thatnmatches @file_obj's pos (which may be the case).nHowever, if @file_obj's pos gets ahead of @offset, this resultsnin #partial_chunked_upload being called with `data = nil`. The clientnwill not complain and the server will respond successfully; returningnthe same @offset it was sent, resulting in a endless loop of PUTnrequests with no body.n

remove timestamp prefix from package filenamesAt one time, the base package filename for all models was 'backup.tar'.nThe timestamp prefix kept these separate in Config.tmp_path.nThese files were also left to accumulate when backups failed.nThis is no longer the case.nnThe base package filename is now the trigger, and any package files leftnfrom a previous failed backup are removed before that model/trigger isnperformed again to prevent these from accumulating.nnThe timestamp prefix was also used at one time by Storages, as this wasntaken from the local filename and used to create the timestamp folder innthe destination path. This is now taken from Package#time.n
